Now suppose is the underlying true distribution of the data, which is unknown. Empirical Processes theory aims at identifying classes formula_6 for which statements such as the following hold:

*uniform law of large numbers:formula_15

:That is, as formula_16,
:formula_17
:uniformly for all formula_18.

*uniform central limit theorem: 
::formula_19

In the former case formula_6 is called &quot;Glivenko–Cantelli&quot; class, and in the latter case (under the assumption formula_21) the class formula_6 is called &quot;Donsker&quot; or -Donsker. A Donsker class is Glivenko–Cantelli in probability by an application of Slutsky&#x27;s theorem .

These statements are true for a single formula_23, by standard LLN, CLT arguments under regularity conditions, and the difficulty in the Empirical Processes comes in because joint statements are being made for all formula_18. Intuitively then, the set formula_6 cannot be too large, and as it turns out that the geometry of formula_6 plays a very important role.

One way of measuring how big the function set formula_6 is to use the so-called covering numbers. The covering number

:formula_28

is the minimal number of balls formula_29 needed to cover the set formula_6 (here it is obviously assumed that there is an underlying norm on formula_6). The entropy is the logarithm of the covering number.

Two sufficient conditions are provided below, under which it can be proved that the set formula_6 is Glivenko–Cantelli or Donsker.

A class formula_6 is -Glivenko–Cantelli if it is -measurable with envelope such that formula_34 and satisfies:

:formula_35

The next condition is a version of the celebrated Dudley&#x27;s theorem. If formula_6 is a class of functions such that

:formula_37

then formula_6 is -Donsker for every probability measure such that formula_39. In the last integral, the notation means

:formula_40.

=== Symmetrization ===
The majority of the arguments of how to bound the empirical process rely on symmetrization, maximal and concentration inequalities, and chaining. Symmetrization is usually the first step of the proofs, and since it is used in many machine learning proofs on bounding empirical loss functions (including the proof of the VC inequality which is discussed in the next section) it is presented here.

Consider the empirical process:

:formula_41

Turns out that there is a connection between the empirical and the following symmetrized process:

:formula_42

The symmetrized process is a Rademacher process, conditionally on the data formula_43. Therefore, it is a sub-Gaussian process by Hoeffding&#x27;s inequality.

Lemma (Symmetrization). For every nondecreasing, convex and class of measurable functions formula_6,

:formula_45

The proof of the Symmetrization lemma relies on introducing independent copies of the original variables formula_46 (sometimes referred to as a &quot;ghost sample&quot;) and replacing the inner expectation of the LHS by these copies. After an application of Jensen&#x27;s inequality different signs could be introduced (hence the name symmetrization) without changing the expectation. The proof can be found below because of its instructive nature. The same proof method can be used to prove the Glivenko–Cantelli theorem.

 = \sup_{f \in \mathcal{F}} \dfrac{1}{n} \left|\sum_{i = 1}^n f(X_i) - \mathbb{E} f(Y_i) \right| \leq \mathbb{E}_{Y} \sup_{f \in \mathcal{F}} \dfrac{1}{n} \left|\sum_{i = 1}^n f(X_i) - f(Y_i) \right|&lt;/math&gt;
Therefore, by Jensen&#x27;s inequality:
:formula_47
Taking expectation with respect to formula_48 gives:
:formula_49
Note that adding a minus sign in front of a term formula_50 doesn&#x27;t change the RHS, because it&#x27;s a symmetric function of formula_48 and formula_52. Therefore, the RHS remains the same under &quot;sign perturbation&quot;:
:formula_53
for any formula_54. Therefore:
:formula_55
Finally using first triangle inequality and then convexity of formula_56 gives:
:formula_57
Where the last two expressions on the RHS are the same, which concludes the proof.

A typical way of proving empirical CLTs, first uses symmetrization to pass the empirical process to formula_58 and then argue conditionally on the data, using the fact that Rademacher processes are simple processes with nice properties.

=== VC Connection ===
It turns out that there is a fascinating connection between certain combinatorial properties of the set formula_6 and the entropy numbers. Uniform covering numbers can be controlled by the notion of &quot;Vapnik–Chervonenkis classes of sets&quot; – or shortly &quot;VC sets&quot;.

Consider a collection formula_60 of subsets of the sample space formula_61. formula_60 is said to &quot;pick out&quot; a certain subset formula_63 of the finite set formula_64 if formula_65 for some formula_66. formula_60 is said to &quot;shatter&quot; if it picks out each of its subsets. The &quot;VC-index&quot; (similar to VC dimension + 1 for an appropriately chosen classifier set) formula_68 of formula_60 is the smallest for which no set of size is shattered by formula_60.

Sauer&#x27;s lemma then states that the number formula_71 of subsets picked out by a VC-class formula_60 satisfies:

:formula_73

Which is a polynomial number formula_74 of subsets rather than an exponential number. Intuitively this means that a finite VC-index implies that formula_60 has an apparent simplistic structure.

