== VC inequality ==
A similar setting is considered, which is more common to machine learning. Let formula_61 is a feature space and formula_104. A function formula_105 is called a classifier. Let formula_6 be a set of classifiers. Similarly to the previous section, define the &quot;shattering coefficient&quot; (also known as growth function):

:formula_107

Note here that there is a 1:1 go between each of the functions in formula_6 and the set on which the function is 1. We can thus define formula_60 to be the collection of subsets obtained from the above mapping for every formula_110. Therefore, in terms of the previous section the shattering coefficient is precisely

:formula_111.

This equivalence together with Sauer&#x27;s Lemma implies that formula_112 is going to be polynomial in , for sufficiently large provided that the collection formula_60 has a finite VC-index.

Let formula_114 is an observed dataset. Assume that the data is generated by an unknown probability distribution formula_115. Define formula_116 to be the expected 0/1 loss. Of course since formula_115 is unknown in general, one has no access to formula_118. However the &quot;empirical risk&quot;, given by:

:formula_119

can certainly be evaluated. Then one has the following Theorem:

===Theorem (VC Inequality)===
For binary classification and the 0/1 loss function we have the following generalization bounds:

:formula_120

In words the VC inequality is saying that as the sample increases, provided that formula_6 has a finite VC dimension, the empirical 0/1 risk becomes a good proxy for the expected 0/1 risk. Note that both RHS of the two inequalities will converge to 0, provided that formula_112 grows polynomially in .

The connection between this framework and the Empirical Process framework is evident. Here one is dealing with a modified empirical process

:formula_123

but not surprisingly the ideas are the same. The proof of the (first part of) VC inequality, relies on symmetrization, and then argue conditionally on the data using concentration inequalities (in particular Hoeffding&#x27;s inequality). The interested reader can check the book Theorems 12.4 and 12.5.

